ts function and leads to adverse neurological effects. Additionally, GABA is implicated in anxiety disorders, potentially due to insufficient benzodiazepine receptor function or a lack of endogenous ligands that normally facilitate its inhibitory effects. Overall, GABA is a vital neurotransmitter with significant roles in brain health, neurochemical balance, and the regulation of anxiety-related processes.\",5\r\n34,BENZODIAZEPINE RECEPTOR,\"The benzodiazepine receptor is a target for benzodiazepine drugs, which have anti-anxiety effects\",3\r\n881,NALOXONE,\"A medication used in the treatment of acute alcohol intoxication and alcohol withdrawal symptoms, administered intravenously.\"\"\",3\r\n809,WITHDRAWAL SYNDROME,\"Withdrawal syndrome, or abstinence syndrome, occurs after reducing or stopping the use of a substance after prolonged and/or high-dose use\",1\r\n814,BARBITURATES,Barbiturates are sedative-hypnotic drugs that can lead to dependence and withdrawal symptoms,4\r\n985,LEAD,Lead is a toxic heavy metal that can cause neurological and hematological damage when absorbed into the body,3\r\n997,LEAD POISONING,,4\r\n990,TETRAETHYL LEAD,\"An organic lead compound used as a gasoline additive, which is highly toxic and affects the central nervous system\",3\r\n77,EPILEPSY,\"Epilepsy is a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent seizures resulting from abnormal electrical activity in the brain. It can develop following various types of brain injuries, with seizures occurring in approximately 5% of closed head injuries, 50% of complex skull fractures, and 30%-50% of open head injuries. Notably, epilepsy may manifest months or even years after the initial injury. During pregnancy, epilepsy poses risks to fetal development, potentially leading to intellectual disability and other developmental issues in the fetus. Additionally, epilepsy is associated with secondary anxiety symptoms, which can further complicate the condition. The management of epilepsy requires